(33, 20, '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '<p>1. above board &ndash; legitimate, legal. She knows it shouldn&rsquo;t be kept a secret. She wants to keep everything above board.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>2. across the board &ndash; including everyone or everything. The company had a successful year. All salaries were increased by 10% across the board.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>3. air one&rsquo;s dirty laundry in public &ndash; discuss personal problems openly. He is a very private person. If he has a problem in his family he doesn&rsquo;t want to air his dirty laundry in public.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>4. all along &ndash; all the time. She was accepted into the university, but she knew all along that she&rsquo;d get in.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>5. all ears &ndash; eager to listen. I was excited to hear about her vacation. When she told me about it, I was all ears.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>6. all thumbs &ndash; clumsy, unable to fix things. Don&rsquo;t ask me to put that clock back together. I&rsquo;m all thumbs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>7. an arm and a leg &ndash; a large amount of money. It cost an arm and a leg to fix the stove.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>8. ants in one&rsquo;s pants &ndash; nervous, anxious. He wasn&rsquo;t sure if he would be chosen to win the award. He had ants in his pants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>9. apple doesn&rsquo;t fall far from the tree, the &ndash; being similar to a parent or family member. He acts just like his father. You know, the apple doesn&rsquo;t fall far from the tree.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>10. apple of one&rsquo;s eye &ndash; someone special, usually a son or daughter. Although he loves his son, his daughter is the apple of his eye.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>11. at fault &ndash; responsible for making errors. He is at fault for all the errors on the computer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>12. at odds &ndash; in disagreement. He is at odds with his boss.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>13. at one&rsquo;s beck and call &ndash; always ready to do what is ordered. Whenever she calls him, he&rsquo;s always helping her. He is at her beck and call. The 800 Most Commo nly Used Idioms in America</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>14. at one&rsquo;s wit&rsquo;s end &ndash; anxious, frantic. I need to speak with him to finish the report by tomorrow but he&rsquo;s not available. I&rsquo;m at my wit&rsquo;s end!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>15. at the end of one&rsquo;s rope &ndash; desperate, with nowhere to turn. I&rsquo;ve tried every which way to figure out this problem but I can&rsquo;t. I&rsquo;m at the end of my rope!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>16. back on one&rsquo;s feet &ndash; financially or physically healthy again. Since sales improved, he is doing better and he&rsquo;s getting back on his feet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>17. back out of &ndash; withdraw, end an obligation or promise. I made a deal with my friend to help him at work. When I became too busy, I had to back out of it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>18. back to the drawing board &ndash; rethink an idea, need to start over. When my supervisor told me that our idea would not work, we had to go back to the drawing board to come up with something else.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>19. backbone &ndash; courage. He has no backbone because he was afraid to reprimand her.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>20. backseat driver &ndash; passenger who tells you how to drive. I&rsquo;ll never drive Joe to the airport again. He kept on wanting me to take another road which I knew was wrong. He is such a backseat driver.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>21. bail one out &ndash; help. Thanks for picking me up when my car broke down. You really bailed me out of a bad situation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>22. ballpark figure &ndash; approximate amount. When I asked the contractor how much it would be to remodel the kitchen, he gave me a ballpark figure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>23. bang for the buck &ndash; value for the money spent. Newspaper advertising works well for us because we get the best bang for the buck.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>24. bank on it &ndash; be sure of, count on. I&rsquo;ll be there to help you. You can bank on it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>25. banker&rsquo;s hours &ndash; short work hours. He loves his job because on Friday, he gets to work banker&rsquo;s hours.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>26. bark up the wrong tree &ndash; make a wrong choice or a false assumption. If he thinks that I&rsquo;m going to help him paint his house, well he&rsquo;s barking up the wrong tree.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>27. bat a thousand &ndash; have a perfect record. He is so happy that everyone he invited to the party is coming. He&rsquo;s batting a thousand.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>28. bat an eyelash &ndash; show emotion. He was filled with emotion during his speech, but she didn&rsquo;t bat an eyelash.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>29. bawl out &ndash; reprimand. The team was bawled out after they lost the game.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>30. be beside one&rsquo;s self &ndash; be very upset. I was so mad when I heard that she was making up stories about me that I was beside myself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>31. beat around the bush &ndash; avoid giving a clear answer. I didn&rsquo;t want to hurt his feelings and tell him that he wasn&rsquo;t selected for the team. So when he asked me if I had any information, I basically beat around the bush.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>32. beat someone to the punch &ndash; do something before someone else can. She was going to buy the last red dress that the store had, but I beat her to the punch and bought it first.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>33. beat the rap &ndash; escape punishment. There was not enough evidence to convict him, so he beat the rap and was set free.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>34. behind the 8-ball &ndash; in trouble. My department is late on its deadline. We are behind the 8-ball.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>35. bend over backwards &ndash; try very hard. He&rsquo;ll bend over backwards to help any of his friends.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>36. bide one&rsquo;s time &ndash; wait patiently for the right opportunity. I&rsquo;m just going to bide my time. I know that eventually a position will open.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>37. big shot &ndash; important person. Since he was given a promotion, he&rsquo;s been acting like a big shot.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>38. big stink &ndash; an angry and loud complaint. She made a big stink when her meal was served cold.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>39. birds and bees - facts about sex and birth. The girl&rsquo;s mother told her daughter about the birds and the bees during the summer holidays.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>40. bit off more than one can chew &ndash; trying to do more than one can physically and mentally handle. I told her I would help her in her job, but it seems that&rsquo;s all I&rsquo;ve been doing lately. I think I bit off more than I could chew.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>41. bite one&rsquo;s tongue &ndash; keep oneself from speaking. I had to bite my tongue in order not to tell him that he won the raffle.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>42. bite the dust &ndash; die, disappear. Our old TV didn&rsquo;t work yesterday. I guess it finally bit the dust.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>43. blab &ndash; talk too much. She is always blabbing about her supervisor&rsquo;s personal life to her friends.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>44. blabbermouth &ndash; person who talks too much and tells secrets. He is such a blabbermouth that there is no way Bob will be surprised for his party.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>45. black sheep &ndash; a family member with a bad reputation. John&rsquo;s way of life is so different from all of ours. He is known as the black sheep of the family.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>46. blind date &ndash; a date arranged for two people who don&rsquo;t know each other. Many married couples have met on a blind date.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>47. blow it &ndash; lose a chance, make a mistake. I knew I blew it when I forgot my lines in the play.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>48. blow over &ndash; end, pass. She knew her coworkers will eventually forget how she messed up the filing system in the office. She couldn&rsquo;t wait for the incident to blow over.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>49. blow the whistle &ndash; expose, betray. I just found out that he&rsquo;s been stealing from our company for the past year. I don&rsquo;t want it to continue and I&rsquo;ve decided to blow the whistle.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>50. boil down &ndash; make shorter, condense. This whole complicated situation just boils down to something simple&hellip;it&rsquo;s either a yes or a no.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>51. bomb &ndash; fail, be unsuccessful. The whole cast was very sad that the show bombed on Broadway.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>52. bone to pick with someone &ndash; complaint, argument. I heard that you have rejected my proposal. I&rsquo;m upset and have a bone to pick with you.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>53. boob tube &ndash; television set. What is on the boob tube tonight?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>54. bookworm &ndash; person who reads a lot. The library is the perfect place for her to work because she is such a bookworm.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>55. booze &ndash; liquor &ndash; They kept bottles of booze behind the bar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>56. botch up &ndash; make a mistake, ruin. I asked for her help with my watercolor painting. But when she decided to add some purple paint, I knew that she completely botched it up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>57. bottom line &ndash; end result, ultimate cause. He never practiced the piano, so the bottom line is, he can&rsquo;t play very well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>58. bounce &ndash; not acceptable because of insufficient funds in the bank. If your check bounces, I will need to charge you extra money.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>59. brain &ndash; intelligent person. She is such a brain, she will figure out how to solve the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>60. brainstorm &ndash; very smart idea. I have got a brainstorm! Let&rsquo;s start giving out free samples of our products.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>61. bread and butter - basic needs of life (food, shelter, clothing). The voters are worried about bread and butter issues like jobs and taxes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>62. break one&rsquo;s neck &ndash; try very hard. She broke her neck last night trying to finalize the proposal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>63. break the ice &ndash; overcome formality or shyness with others. He started the meeting by telling a joke. He was hoping the joke would break the ice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>64. break the news &ndash; tell a surprising fact. She broke the news and told him that she was going to move to another city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>65. break up &ndash; separate. They needed to break up their engagement because she fell in love with someone else.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>66. break even &ndash; have expenses equal to profits. The company did not make a profit this year. We just broke even.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>67. breathe a word &ndash; tell. Please don&rsquo;t breathe a word of this to anyone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>68. breeze &ndash; easy. Last night&rsquo;s homework was a breeze.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>69. bring home the bacon &ndash; earn the family&rsquo;s income. He stays home and raises the children and she brings home the bacon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>70. broke &ndash; having no money. I can&rsquo;t go to the restaurant tonight because I&rsquo;m broke.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>71. brown bag &ndash; bring one&rsquo;s lunch from home. For the meeting on Friday, we&rsquo;ve all decided to brown bag it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>72. buck &ndash; dollar. I&rsquo;m low this week on cash. Can I borrow a few bucks to get me through the week?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>73. buckle down &ndash; study or work very hard. Last semester his grades were very low, so this year he decided to buckle down.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>74. buddy-buddy &ndash; very friendly. She&rsquo;s gotten to be very buddy-buddy with her boss.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>75. bug &ndash; annoy, bother. It bugs me every time he asks to borrow a pencil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>76. bulldoze &ndash; intimidate, coerce. I did not want to work on the fundraising committee, but I feel I was bulldozed into it&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>77. bum &ndash; worthless person. As long as I have known him, he never worked and always borrowed from other people. He is such a bum!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>78. burn a hole in one&rsquo;s pocket &ndash; money to be spent quickly. The bonus he received must have burned a hole in his pocket. He ended up buying a car the next day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>79. bury the hatchet &ndash; make peace. Although we had gotten into a big fight last month, we decided to bury the hatchet and become friends again.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>80. butt in &ndash; interfere. Please don&rsquo;t butt in to our conversation, it&rsquo;s personal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>81. butter up &ndash; flatter for selfish reasons. I buttered up my boss before I asked him off for the upcoming holiday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>82. by hook or by crook &ndash; by any means necessary. Even though we have to fly to get to your wedding, we will be there by hook or by crook.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>83. by the skin of one&rsquo;s teeth &ndash; by a very small margin. Our team won by the skin of our teeth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>84. call it quits &ndash; stop, finish. I have worked all day and am exhausted. I&lsquo;ve decided to call it quits.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>85. call off &ndash; cancel. The game was called off because of rain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>86. call on the carpet &ndash; reprimand. He was called on the carpet for losing all the financial statements.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>87. call someone&rsquo;s bluff &ndash; have someone prove what he says. I don&rsquo;t think Bob knows as much as he says. I think we should call his bluff.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>88. call the shots &ndash; be in charge, give orders. We knew who the supervisor was because she called all the shots.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>89. can &ndash; fire, dismiss. I was canned and no longer am working for the company.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>90. can of worms - complex problem or complicated situation. It opened up a large can of worms when the company decided to talk about the union contract.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>91. carried away &ndash; adversely influenced by strong emotion. He was carried away by his effective sales approach and bought the remainder of his products.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>92. catch on &ndash; understand, figure out. I am beginning to catch on to this algebra.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>93. catch someone red-handed &ndash; find one in the act of doing something wrong. The police came and the bank robber was caught red handed&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>94. caught short &ndash; I didn&rsquo;t have enough money to pay the bill. I was caught short.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>95. chalk up &ndash; record, score. Chalk up another one for the team. They won the championship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>96. change of heart - a change in the way one feels about something. I wasn&rsquo;t planning to spend the holidays with my family, but after speaking with my mother, I had a change of heart.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>97. chickenfeed &ndash; a small amount of money. Taking the whole family on that cruise is certainly not going to be chickenfeed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>98. chip in &ndash; contribute. We are all going to chip in and give the teacher a gift.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>99. chip off the old block &ndash; child who looks or acts just like his or her parent. He reminds me so much of his father. He&rsquo;s a chip off the old block.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>100. chip on one&rsquo;s shoulder &ndash; quarrelsome attitude, quick to anger. I was afraid to ask her for a favor. It looked like she had a chip on her shoulder.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>'),
(35, 20, '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '<p>&nbsp;201. for the birds &ndash; terrible, awful. I work long hours and hardly get paid. This job is for the birds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>202. for the time being &ndash; at the present time. For the time being, let&rsquo;s not make any changes to the report.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>203. free-for-all &ndash; mayhem, disorder. When the teacher left for a meeting, it was a free-for-all in the classroom.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>204. freeload &ndash; get things that others pay for. When my friend moved into my apartment, stayed for a year and never contributed any money, I knew he was a freeloader.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>205. from the bottom of one&rsquo;s heart - with great feeling, sincerely. My sister thanked me from the bottom of her heart for saving her dog&rsquo;s life.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>206. from the left field &ndash; unexpectedly, with an odd or unclear connection to the subject. We were in the middle of a business meeting when, out from left field, he asked about the weather.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>207. from scratch &ndash; from the very beginning, starting with raw materials. This chocolate was not made from a cake mix, she made it from scratch.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>208. fume &ndash; be angry. When I heard that she was talking about me to other people, I was just fuming.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>209. gall &ndash; shameless, insolent attitude. She spent all of her money on clothes and music, and then she asked to borrow money for groceries. She has gall.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>210. game &ndash; willing, ready. Okay, you want to make plans to go to China? Okay, I&rsquo;m game.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>211. get a grip on oneself &ndash; take control of one&rsquo;s feelings . When he lost the soccer game, he couldn&rsquo;t stop crying. I told him to get a grip on himself.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>212. get a kick out of &ndash; enjoy. I get a kick out of it every time I see her dance.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>213. get a load of &ndash; have a good look at. Get a load of those fancy cars driving down the street.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>214. get ahead &ndash; become successful. She is saving all her money, so that one day she can get ahead.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>215. get along &ndash; manage. He realized that he was able to get along quite well without his partner.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>216. get around to - finally find time to do something &ndash; I have put it off for months, but I finally got around to cleaning the windows.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>217. get at &ndash; mean, hint. You tell me that I am slow at work. What are trying to get at.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>218. get away with murder &ndash; not be punished for wrongdoing. &ndash; He&rsquo;s the boss&rsquo;s son and comes in late everyday, but we can&rsquo;t complain. He&rsquo;s getting away with murder.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>219. get cold feet &ndash; be afraid at the last minute, lose confidence. I was prepared to make a speech, but I got cold feet when I saw how many people were going to hear it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>220. get down to brass tacks &ndash; begin important work or business. Get off the phone so that we can discuss business. Let&rsquo;s get down to brass tacks.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>221. get even &ndash; get revenge, settle the score. I was so upset when she insulted me last week. I want to get even with her.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>222. get the runaround &ndash; be sent from place to place without getting the information needed. It took me four hours to renew my driver&rsquo;s license. I was sent to almost every department and seemed to get the runaround.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>223. get in on the ground floor &ndash; start from the beginning so you&rsquo;ll have full advantage of any favorable outcome. He is a very wealthy man. He was one Microsoft&rsquo;s first employees and got in on the ground floor.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>224. get in the swing of things &ndash; adapt or adjust to a new environment. After working two weeks in the new department, I finally got into the swing of things.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>225. get off the ground - make a successful beginning, go ahead. He will finally take his project and get it off the ground in the coming year.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>226. get off one&rsquo;s back &ndash; leave someone alone, don&rsquo;t bother. She reminded me that I had to prepare for my trip out of town. I wish she would get off my back.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>227. get off on the wrong foot &ndash; make a bad start. Having a fight with a co-worker on my first day of work was not a good idea. I got off on the wrong foot.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>228. get off the ground &ndash; make progress, make a good start. I finally got my business off the ground.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>229. get one&rsquo;s goat &ndash; make someone disgusted, annoyed, angry. Sitting in traffic for 5 hours really got my goat.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>230. get out from under &ndash; end a worrisome situation. I am glad that I am working again and making money. I finally got out from under my bills.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>231. get out of &ndash; withdraw. I would really like to get out of going to the holiday party.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>232. get out of hand &ndash; lose control. The party really got out of hand when they started drinking alcohol.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>233. get something off one&rsquo;s chest &ndash; unburden yourself, tell what&rsquo;s bothering you. I feel better ever since I told him my problem and got it off my chest.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>234. get the ax &ndash; be fired. My company finally realized that he wasn&rsquo;t doing his job. They gave him the ax.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>235. get the show on the road &ndash; start a project or work. We have been discussing unimportant things all morning. Let&rsquo;s get the show on the road and start getting down to business.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>236. get to the bottom of &ndash; find out the real cause. After talking to my friend for an hour, I finally got to the bottom of why he was angry at me.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>237. get under someone&rsquo;s skin - annoy, bother, upset. He has a difficult and annoying personality and always got under my skin.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>238. get up and go &ndash; ambition, energy, enthusiasm &ndash; She always seems so excited and motivated at work. She&rsquo;s got a lot of get up and go.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>239. get up on the wrong side of the bed &ndash; be in a bad mood. My son has been cranky all day. I think he got up on the wrong side of the bed.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>240. get what is coming to one &ndash; what one deserves, good or bad. After stealing so much money from the charity, I really hope he gets what&rsquo;s coming to him.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>241. get wind of &ndash; find out, hear gossip or rumors about. I got wind of the fact that they will be closing down our department.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>242. give a hoot &ndash; care. I don&rsquo;t give a hoot who wins the election.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>243. give the cold shoulder &ndash; be unfriendly to, ignore. I was so mad at my cousin, that I gave her the cold shoulder at the wedding reception.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>244. give in &ndash; do as others want, surrender. I wanted to paint the room blue, my wife wanted yellow. I had to give in.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>245. give it one&rsquo;s best shot &ndash; try very hard. I gave it my best shot, but I still didn&rsquo;t make the team.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>246. give someone a break &ndash; give someone an opportunity or chance. The actor struggled for many years. Finally, someone gave him a break and put him in a movie.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>247. give someone a hand &ndash; help. I couldn&rsquo;t work my regular hours. A co-worker gave me a hand and switched schedules with me.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>248. give someone a piece of one&rsquo;s mind &ndash; say what you really think when angry. I was so mad that he was late for the wedding, I gave him a piece of my mind.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>249. give someone his walking papers &ndash; dismiss, fire, send away. She got her walking papers on Friday and won&rsquo;t be coming back to work.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>250. give someone the green light - give permission to go ahead with a project. We were finally given the green light to begin setting up the new project.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>251. go cold turkey &ndash; stop abruptly. My doctor really wants me to quit smoking. I decided to stop and go cold turkey.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>252. go Dutch &ndash; each person pay for himself. If we have dinner together, I insist that we go Dutch.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>253. go from bad to worse &ndash; deteriorate. Sales have been very slow this season, but this was the worst week of all. It seems like it&rsquo;s going from bad to worse.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>254. go out of one&rsquo;s way &ndash; make a special effort, do more than necessary. I went out of my way to make it easier for you.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>255. go over &ndash; examine. Before I submit the report, I want to go over it one more time for mistakes.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>256. go over big &ndash; be very successful. Do you think my idea to have a birthday party for our teacher will go over big?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>257. go overboard &ndash; overact, be reckless. I&rsquo;ve never seen so many flowers at a wedding. Do you think maybe you&rsquo;ve gone overboard?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>258. go steady &ndash; go out with only one person romantically. Who did you go steady with in high school?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>259. go to bat for &ndash; assist, help. I have overheard that she may be fired from her job. I think she is a hard worker and I want her to stay. I&rsquo;m going to bat for her.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>260. go to pot &ndash; deteriorate, become undisciplined, unkempt. He has quit his job, gained weight, and I think may be abusing drugs. It looks like he&rsquo;s really gone to pot.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>261. go under the knife &ndash; have surgery. I&rsquo;ll be going under the knife next week for some minor surgery.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>262. go up in smoke &ndash; disappear, fail to materialize. She was going to go on a vacation, but her mother got sick. Her plans have gone up in smoke.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>263. go-getter &ndash; ambitious person. She is the most successful salesperson I&rsquo;ve ever seen. She&rsquo;s a real go-getter.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>264. goldmine &ndash; worth a lot of money, successful. His business is a major success and will only get bigger every year. He is sitting on a goldmine.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>265. goner &ndash; someone in a lot of trouble. His boss found out he has been stealing from the cash register. He&rsquo;s a goner.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>266. good sport &ndash; a person who loses well. Even though I beat you in the game, you still congratulated me. You are a good sport.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>267. goof off &ndash; not want to work, be lazy. I am tired of working so hard. I just want to stay home and goof off.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>268. grab 40 winks &ndash; I felt so sleepy after my lunch, I decided to grab 40 winks.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>269. grand - $1000. It cost me a grand to stay in the luxury hotel.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>270. greasy spoon &ndash; inexpensive restaurant with mediocre food. I hated dinner last night. It turned out being a greasy spoon.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>271. gung ho &ndash; enthusiastic, eager. He thinks his team is the best in the league. He is really gung ho this season.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>272. guts &ndash; courage. He has a lot of guts to stand up to management.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>273. guy &ndash; man. That guy over there is my neighbor.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>274. half baked &ndash; foolish, silly. Opening up a store which sells only tape will not be successful. It is a half baked idea.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>275. hand it to someone &ndash; give credit, acknowledge. I&rsquo;ve got to hand it to you. Your idea to open a store in this location was great.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>276. hand over fist &ndash; rapidly. He&rsquo;s making money hand over fist.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>277. hand something on a silver platter - give a person something that has not been earned. His father is president of the university and his education was handed to him on a silver platter.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>278. hand to mouth &ndash; barely able to cover basic expenses. That family is struggling since the father lost his job. I hear that they&rsquo;re living hand to mouth.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>279. handful &ndash; a lot of trouble. My three year old runs around the house and often breaks things. He&rsquo;s a real handful.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>280. handle with kid gloves &ndash; be very careful, tactful. His wife gets upset very easily. He has to handle her with kid gloves.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>281. handy &ndash; can fix things, useful. She&rsquo;s very handy around the house. If anything breaks, she can fix it easily.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>282. hang in there &ndash; be patient, wait. I know you want to quit school, but hang in there. You only have 4 more weeks before your graduation.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>283. hard feelings &ndash; anger, bitterness. I know we had our differences, but I hope there are not any hard feelings.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>284. hard up &ndash; in desperate need of something. Everyone comes to her desk and takes supplies. I know she&rsquo;s hard up for pencils.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>285. harp on &ndash; dwell on the subject, repeat, persist. I know losing your job was awful, but don&rsquo;t harp on it. You are only making yourself more depressed.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>286. has-been &ndash; a person once popular but no longer in public favor. Since the movie star was found guilty of a crime, I haven&rsquo;t seen him in any motion pictures. He&rsquo;s a has-been.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>287. hassle &ndash; bother. Please stay home tonight. I don&rsquo;t want the hassle of having to bring you and pick you up from the party.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>288. have a ball &ndash; have a good time, enjoy one&rsquo;s self. She had a ball at her holiday party.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>289. have a crush on &ndash; be attracted to. I have had a crush on her since 5th grade.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>290. have a fit &ndash; become upset. She&rsquo;ll have a fit if she finds out you broke her watch.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>291. have a good head on one&rsquo;s shoulders &ndash; be smart or sensible. You have a good head on your shoulders and I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;ll do fine in college.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>292. have a mind of one&rsquo;s own &ndash; be able to think independently. Although we all voted one way, she voted in a completely opposite direction. She&rsquo;s really got a mind of her own.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>293. have a prayer &ndash; have a chance. He&rsquo;s not good enough to make it on the team. He doesn&rsquo;t have a prayer.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>294. have been around &ndash; to be experienced, sophisticated. She knows all about office politics. She has been around for awhile.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>295. have egg on one&rsquo;s face &ndash; be embarrassed. She called in sick to work yesterday, but when I saw her at the store she had egg on her face.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>296. have it coming &ndash; deserve a punishment. I didn&rsquo;t study for the exam and I failed. I had it coming.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>297. have it made &ndash; be sure of success, have everything. Ever since she won the lottery, she can do whatever she wants. She has it made.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>298. have it out with someone &ndash; discuss a conflict or misunderstanding with the other person involved. My friend and I had a big fight last week. This morning I had it out with him and now everything is okay.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>299. have one&rsquo;s feet on the ground &ndash; be practical, sensible, stable. She&rsquo;ll make a great wife and mother because she has got both feet on the ground.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>300. have one&rsquo;s hand in the till &ndash; steal from one&rsquo;s employer. The reason he has been buying such nice new clothes is that he&rsquo;s got his hand in the till.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>');
INSERT INTO `cn_ecms_news_data_1` (`id`, `classid`, `keyid`, `dokey`, `newstempid`, `closepl`, `haveaddfen`, `infotags`, `writer`, `befrom`, `newstext`) VALUES
(36, 20, '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '<p>&nbsp;301. have one&rsquo;s head in the clouds &ndash; have unrealistic dreams, lost in thought. Even though she is a terrible actress, she thinks someday she will be a movie star. She has got her head in the clouds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>302. have one&rsquo;s heart set on &ndash; desire greatly. The boy had his heart set on getting a puppy.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>303. have someone&rsquo;s number &ndash; know what kind of person someone is. He doesn&rsquo;t think anyone knows, but I know he stole the material for the book. I&rsquo;ve got his number.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>304. have something up one&rsquo;s sleeve &ndash; kept secretly ready for the right time. If the electricity goes out during the birthday party, don&rsquo;t worry. I&rsquo;ve got something up my sleeve.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>305. have the heart to &ndash; be thoughtless enough. I know there was just a death in her family. I don&rsquo;t have the heart to ask her when she is coming back to work.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>306. have two strikes against someone &ndash; be in a difficult situation with little chance of success. He wanted the job but he can&rsquo;t write and he has difficulty speaking on the phone. He&rsquo;s got two strikes against him already.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>307. haywire &ndash; broken, confused, awry. The plan was in place to surprise by boss on his birthday, but it all went haywire.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>308. heart-to-heart &ndash; intimate, honest. I needed to speak him about a problem I was having. We had a heart-to-heart talk.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>309. high and dry &ndash; alone, without help, stranded. After everyone left the party, I was all alone to clean up. I was left high and dry.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>310. high and low &ndash; every place. I can&rsquo;t seem to find my keys. I&rsquo;ve looked high and low.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>311. high-brow &ndash; intellectual, cultured person. Everyone seemed very high-brow at the cocktail reception.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>312. hit &ndash; a success. Her book was a hit and sold a million copies.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>313. hit below the belt &ndash; hurt someone cruelly and unfairly. I have been upset ever since she made that awful comment to me. It really hit below the belt.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>314. hit it off &ndash; enjoy one another&rsquo;s company, get along. Although we just met, we really hit it off and will probably see each other again.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>315. hit the bottle &ndash; drink alcohol. He hits the bottle every time he has some family trouble.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>316. hit the ceiling &ndash; get angry. I hit the ceiling when I found out that she broke my computer.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>317. hit the nail on the head &ndash; arrive at the correct answer, make a precise analysis. When you named the person who was responsible for our losses this quarter, you really hit the nail on the head.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>318. hit the sack &ndash; go to bed. I was so tired last night, that I hit the sack as soon as I got home.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>319. hit the spot &ndash; refresh or satisfy. We sat in the sun and hadn&rsquo;t had a drink all day. That cold glass of water really hit the spot.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>320. hogwash &ndash; nonsense. The idea that aliens landed in New York City is a bunch of hogwash.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>321. hold a grudge &ndash; not forgive someone for an insult or injury. Even though they broke up 10 years ago, she still holds a grudge and will not speak to him.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>322. hold back &ndash; conceal, hide. He held back his feelings and acted as if everything was alright.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>323. hold one&rsquo;s horses &ndash; wait. I can&rsquo;t leave the office yet. I&rsquo;m waiting for an important phone call. Just hold your horses.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>324. hold up &ndash; delay, postpone. Sorry I&rsquo;m late. I was held up in traffic.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>325. holy mackerel - used to express strong feeling of surprise. Holy Mackerel! Look at that man&rsquo;s motorcycle.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>326. hook, line and sinker &ndash; without question or doubt. I told a lie to my teacher. He bought it hook, line and sinker.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>327. hot1 &ndash; stolen. He bought a great television from a guy on the street for $50.00. The television must have been hot.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>328. hot2 &ndash; in great demand. This was the hottest movie out this weekend.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>329. hot air &ndash; nonsense or exaggerated talk. I don&rsquo;t believe a word that man says. He is full of hot air.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>330. hound &ndash; continually bother. She hounded me until I finally agreed to say yes.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>331. hush-hush &ndash; secret. The birthday party is a surprise. Please don&rsquo;t tell anyone, it&rsquo;s hush-hush.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>332. hustler &ndash; person who gets money aggressively or unethically. He won&rsquo;t work. If he needs money, he&rsquo;ll hustle someone.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>333. hyper &ndash; very energetic, anxious, unable to sit still. It is impossible to bring that child to a restaurant. He is too hyper.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>334. ill at ease &ndash; I am shy. So when I go to a cocktail party I am ill at ease.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>335. in a bind. In trouble no matter what you do. She committed to help two different people at the same time. She is in a bind.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>336. in a jam &ndash; in trouble. He is in a jam and needs some help to get out of it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>337. in a nutshell &ndash; briefly. She spoke to us for at least an hour and told us a long story. I would have preferred that we heard it in a nutshell.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>338. in a pinch &ndash; okay, when nothing else is available. If you don&rsquo;t have a needle to sew something together, a safety pin will work in a pinch.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>339. in a rush &ndash; in a hurry. I can&rsquo;t find my wallet and keys and I&rsquo;m late for a meeting. I&rsquo;m in a rush.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>340. in a rut &ndash; always doing the same thing. My job is very boring and uninteresting. I&rsquo;m depressed and think I am in a rut.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>341. in advance &ndash; ahead of time. Let&rsquo;s call the movie theatre in advance and see if they have any tickets left.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>342. in black and white &ndash; in writing. The salesman said that he would give me a 5 year warranty on my purchase. I told him to put it in black and white.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>343. in hot water &ndash; in trouble. I am going to be in hot water when she finds out that I dented her car.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>344. in nothing flat &ndash; quickly, in a short time. When he heard that I was taking him out to dinner, he got dressed in nothing flat.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>345. in seventh heaven &ndash; very happy. I begin my month long vacation tomorrow. I&rsquo;m in seventh heaven.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>346. in someone&rsquo;s shoes &ndash; in another person&rsquo;s place or position. You cannot pass judgment on someone until you&rsquo;ve stepped into their shoes.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>347. in stitches &ndash; laughing. He is the funniest person I know. He always keeps me in stitches.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>348. in the bag &ndash; certain, sure, definite. The job interview went very well and I think I will be hired. I am confident that it&rsquo;s in the bag.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>349. in the doghouse &ndash; in trouble. My wife and I had a big fight last night. I&rsquo;m in the doghouse.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>350. in the long run &ndash; in the end, as a result. If you study hard in school, in the long run you will be successful.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>351. in the market for &ndash; wanting or ready to buy. We are in the market for a new mattress.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>352. in the red &ndash; losing money. Our company is in the red and may be going out of business.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>353. in the same boat &ndash; in a similar situation. He can&rsquo;t pay his bills either. He is in the same boat as you.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>354. iron out &ndash; work out. Even though the two men do not get along, they are both willing to iron out their problems.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>355. jack up &ndash; raise prices. Last week the department store jacked up all their prices.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>356. jack-of-all-trades - person who can do many kinds of work. My friend is a jack-of-all-trades. He knows how to fix everything.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>357. jalopy &ndash; old car usually in poor condition. I finally sold my jalopy and bought a new car.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>358. jam-packed &ndash; crowded, full. My new computer can do so many different things. It&rsquo;s jam-packed with features.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>359. the jitters &ndash; anxiety, nervousness. She knew the test was going to be very difficult and she had the jitters all day.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>360. John Hancock &ndash; signature. The car salesman asked the customer to put his John Hancock on the bottom of the contract.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>361. jump down someone&rsquo;s throat &ndash; criticize angrily, hastily. He&rsquo;s very angry today. Every time I ask him a question he jumps down my throat.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>362. jump the gun &ndash; start before you should. You will need more facts before you go into business. Don&rsquo;t jump the gun.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>363. jump to conclusions &ndash; make quick but unjustified conclusions. Don&rsquo;t jump to conclusions and assume that all well-dressed men are rich.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>364. keep a stiff upper lip &ndash; have courage, be brave. Even though he thought he was going to be terminated from his job, he kept a stiff upper lip.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>365. keep in touch &ndash; communicate, talk or write to each other &ndash; Even though we won&rsquo;t see each other for six months, let&rsquo;s try to keep in touch.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>366. keep on &ndash; continue. If you are not hungry, don&rsquo;t keep on eating.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>367. keep one&rsquo;s fingers crossed &ndash; wish for good luck. His mother kept her fingers crossed so that her son would make the team.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>368. keep one&rsquo;s head above water &ndash; be able to exist on one&rsquo;s income, pay bills. Even though she only made a meager salary, she was still able to buy clothes, go to restaurants, and keep her head above water.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>369. keep one&rsquo;s nose clean &ndash; After he was released from prison he stayed out of trouble. His parents were glad that he kept his nose clean.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>370. keep one&rsquo;s shirt on &ndash; be patient, wait. I know it&rsquo;s taking me a long time to finish my work, but keep your shirt on.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>371. keep something under your hat &ndash; keep something a secret. She was given information which was meant to be private, so she kept it under her hat&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>372. keep tabs on &ndash; watch, check. My neighbor is always looking out her window and keeping tabs on me.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>373. Keep up with the Joneses &ndash; try to equal your neighbor&rsquo;s lifestyle. He works many long hours just so he can keep up with the Joneses.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>374. kick in the pants &ndash; rejection, criticism. Steve was always kind to someone who was poor and unfortunate. When that person made a lot of money, he ignored Steve. Steve got a kick in the pants.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>375. kick oneself &ndash; regret. I could kick myself for not buying that stock which tripled in value.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>376. kick something around &ndash; discuss, think about. We didn&rsquo;t know which way to direct the company, so we kicked some ideas around.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>377. kick the bucket &ndash; die. The old man kicked the bucket when he was 110 years old.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>378. kid &ndash; a young person. I have two kids. They are 10 and 3 years old.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>379. kid around &ndash; fool, play, joke. Don&rsquo;t kid around with Mary. She is in a very bad mood.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>380. kiss something goodbye &ndash; see something ruined or lost. When I saw the photo album fall off of the boat and into the water, I knew it was lost forever and I just kissed it goodbye.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>381. knock it off &ndash; stop. He wouldn&rsquo;t stop tickling me, so I told him to knock it off.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>382. knock one dead &ndash; greatly impress, surprise. When the actor was preparing to go on stage, I told me to knock them dead.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>383. knock one for a loop &ndash; surprise. I didn&rsquo;t expect the movie to have that sort of ending. It knocked me for a loop.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>384. knock one&rsquo;s head against the wall &ndash; waste time in futile effort to improve or change something. Teaching teenagers to drive responsibly is like knocking my head against a wall.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>385. knock oneself out &ndash; make a great effort. She worked many hours getting ready for the party and knocked herself out.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>386. knockout, a &ndash; a beautiful person or thing. That beauty queen is a knockout.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>387. know if one is coming or going &ndash; be able to think clearly, know what to do. There were so many students signing up at registration, I didn&rsquo;t know if I was coming or going.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>388. know-how &ndash; experience and knowledge. He has been building houses for many years and has a lot of know-how.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>389. kosher &ndash; true, authentic. The financial statements say that your business is making a lot of money. Are the amounts all kosher?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>390. land on one&rsquo;s feet &ndash; come out of a bad situation successfully. She just came off of a terrible divorce. She&rsquo;s doing well now and it seems that she landed on her feet.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>391. last straw, the &ndash; the last insult or injury that one can endure. His son watched TV all day and didn&rsquo;t work. When he started to gamble, that was the last straw.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>392. lay out &ndash; spend or pay. Will you lay out the money for the meal and I will pay you back tomorrow?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>393. learn the ropes &ndash; acquire special knowledge of a job. Now that you have started your new position with the company, it will probably take you a few months to learn the ropes.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>394. leave a bad taste in one&rsquo;s mouth - make a bad impression, make or feel disgusted. I thought the salesman was obnoxious. He left a bad taste in my mouth.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>395. leave someone holding the bag &ndash; put someone in an awkward position, leave someone else to take the blame. The children ate all of the cookies and ran away. Peter was the only one who remained and was left holding the bag.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>396. lemon &ndash; merchandise that doesn&rsquo;t work. My new car has needed repair four times since I bought it. I ended up buying a lemon.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>397. let bygones be bygones. &ndash; Forget differences that happened in the past. Even though my friend and I had a big fight, I told him we should let bygones be bygones.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>398. let it ride &ndash; continue without changing a situation. Don&rsquo;t say anything to him now. I don&rsquo;t want to hurt his feelings. Just let it ride.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>399. let on &ndash; reveal, inform, tell. She let on that she knew my secret.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>400. let one&rsquo;s hair down &ndash; be informal, relaxed. After the business meeting when our supervisor left, we spoke about our personal lives and let our hair down.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>'),
(37, 20, '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '<p>401. let someone off the hook &ndash; excuse from a penalty or promise. Because this was his first criminal offense, he was let off the hook.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>402. let the cat out of the bag &ndash; tell a secret. His surprise birthday party was cancelled because someone let the cat out of the bag.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>403. Let the chips fall where they may. &ndash; Act regardless of consequences. The police were asking him about the robbery. He knew he had to tell everything he knew and let the chips fall as they may.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>404. like a ton of bricks &ndash; strongly, forcefully. When I was told that my favorite uncle died, it hit him like a ton of bricks.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>405. live high off the hog &ndash; have many luxuries, be very comfortable. When you see their new home, you&rsquo;ll know that they live high off the hog.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>406. live it up &ndash; pursue pleasure, have a good time. Now that school is over, I want to live it up this weekend.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>407. live wire &ndash; active exciting person. People always want her at their parties because she is a live wire.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>408. loaded &ndash; having lots of money. Ever since he started his new business, he appears to be loaded.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>409. loaded &ndash; drunk. I can tell by the way she spoke that she was loaded.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>410. look down one&rsquo;s nose at &ndash; think someone is worthless or unimportant, show contempt. She thinks she is better than everyone else. She always looks down her nose at others.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>411. look into &ndash; investigate, check. I&rsquo;m going to look into the possibility of getting a scholarship for college.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>412. look up &ndash; improve, getting better. Since he is putting in more hours at work, his financial situation is looking up.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>413. loony bin &ndash; insane asylum. I couldn&rsquo;t believe how crazy she acted last night. She belongs in the loony bin!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>414. loot &ndash; money. How much loot do you need to buy that fancy car?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>415. lose one&rsquo;s marbles &ndash; go insane, act irrationally. Anyone who insults his boss has lost his marbles.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>416. lose one&rsquo;s shirt &ndash; lose all one&rsquo;s money. He put his lifetime savings into the restaurant. When it failed, he lost his shirt.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>417. lose track of someone &ndash; lose contact, no know where someone is. I have lost track of him since high school and have no idea where he lives now.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>418. louse up &ndash; ruin. I&rsquo;ve worked on this painting for weeks, but when my paintbrush slipped out of my hand, I loused up the painting.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>419. lowdown &ndash; the true story. I heard that she was married before but didn&rsquo;t know why she divorced. Give me the lowdown.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>420. lower the boom &ndash; stop completely, punish strictly. When the father heard that the children were not doing their homework, he lowered the boom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>421. make a bundle &ndash; make a lot of money. She made a bundle selling donuts to the construction workers.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>422. make a dent in &ndash; make progress. I have got a lot of work to do, but I made a dent in it last night.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>423. make a federal case out of &ndash; overreact, take strong measures for a minor problem. I&rsquo;m sorry for spilling some water on your desk, but you don&rsquo;t have to make a federal case out of it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>424. make a go of &ndash; succeed, produce good results. Although this new business is risky, I&rsquo;m going to try to make a go of it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>425. make a hit &ndash; be successful. People loved my new brownies and wanted the recipe. I guess I made a hit.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>426. make a killing &ndash; gain a large amount of money at one time. She made a killing in the stock market last year.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>427. make a monkey out of someone &ndash; cause to look foolish. The lawyer was shrewd and made a monkey out of his opponent&rsquo;s client.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>428. make a mountain out of a molehill &ndash; make a big problem out of a small one. It wasn&rsquo;t difficult, it was easy. Don&rsquo;t make a mountain out of a molehill.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>429. make ends meet &ndash; balance one&rsquo;s budget, meet one&rsquo;s payments. His expenses are so high, that even though he makes a lot of money, his family has difficulty making ends meet.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>430. make fun of &ndash; ridicule It&rsquo;s not nice to make fun of other people.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>431. make it up to someone &ndash; compensate for an unfulfilled promise. I am so sorry that we have to cancel our plans tonight, but I will try to make it up to you. [!--empirenews.page--]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>432. make of something &ndash; interpret, figure out, think of. What do you make of his decision to drop out of college?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>433. make one&rsquo;s hair stand on end &ndash; frighten, horrify. The extreme poverty in that country would make your hair stand on end.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>434. make one&rsquo;s mouth water - look or smell very good, make one want to eat or drink something one sees or smells &ndash; The smell of garlic outside the restaurant made my mouth water.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>435. make one&rsquo;s own way &ndash; rely on one&rsquo;s own abilities. She had no help from anyone. She had to make her own way.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>436. make out &ndash; do, progress, succeed. How are you making out with your new responsibilities at the office?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>437. make sense &ndash; be comprehensible. What&rsquo;s the word in English that&rsquo;s spelled yrkszwa&hellip;it doesn&rsquo;t make sense.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>438. make sure &ndash; see about something yourself, check. We are leaving on our vacation, and I want to make sure that you locked all the doors.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>439. make the best of &ndash; accept a bad situation and do as well as possible under the circumstances. Even though our heating system broke, let&rsquo;s light a fire in the fireplace and make the best of it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>440. make up one&rsquo;s mind &ndash; decide. She hasn&rsquo;t made up her mind as to what university she will be attending.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>441. make waves &ndash; upset the status quo, create a disturbance. He likes to avoid controversy and usually doesn&rsquo;t make waves.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>442. man-to-man &ndash; frank, direct. Don&rsquo;t discuss the problem with me. Go to your boss&rsquo;s office and talk about it man-to-man.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>443. mean business &ndash; be serious. He told his son that he had to finish all of his homework before he went out to play and he meant business.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>444. mess &ndash; disorderly, cluttered condition; bad or confused situation. There were clothes and food all over his apartment and it was a mess.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>445. miss a trick &ndash; take advantage of every situation. As soon as her boss left the building, she began to make personal calls. She doesn&rsquo;t miss a trick.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>446. miss out on &ndash; lose an opportunity, miss a worthwhile event. It is too bad you couldn&rsquo;t make it to the reunion because you missed out on a good time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>447. miss the boat &ndash; lose an opportunity. It&rsquo;s too bad he didn&rsquo;t buy gold when it was cheap. Now, it is very expensive and he really missed the boat.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>448. mobbed &ndash; crowded. The shopping mall was mobbed the day before Christmas.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>449. mooch &ndash; borrow, beg, get without paying. She says that she doesn&rsquo;t smoke, but she is always mooching cigarettes from her friends.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>450. mouthful &ndash; a true and impressive statement. You said a mouthful when you admitted that she was the smartest girl in her class.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>451. mudslinging &ndash; making malicious remarks to damage someone&rsquo;s reputation. There is a lot of mudslinging going on in politics today.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>452. mum&rsquo;s the word &ndash; don&rsquo;t talk about what was said. I don&rsquo;t want you to say anything about our discussion. Mum&rsquo;s the word.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>453. murder &ndash; a difficult or painful ordeal. Getting her master&rsquo;s degree while she worked full-time was murder.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>454. nag, a &ndash; a persistently urging person. He complains that his wife is always nagging him to do things around the house.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>455. name someone after &ndash; give the child the name of an admired person. My son is named after my grandfather.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>456. nest egg &ndash; extra money saved. They have a small nest egg saved up for their vacation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>457. nightcap, a &ndash; last drink one has before leaving or prior to sleeping. She ordered some brandy as a nightcap.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>458. nincompoop &ndash; a stupid person, a fool. He doesn&rsquo;t know how to act well around other people. He&rsquo;s a nincompoop!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>459. nip in the bud &ndash; prevent at the start. When she saw that her little boy was snacking between meals, she decided to nip it in the bud.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>460. nitpick &ndash; look for very minor errors or problems. Every time she reads one of his reports, she is always nitpicking on the most minor points.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>461. nitty-gritty &ndash; the essence or important part. We&rsquo;ve been discussing your problem for an hour, but we finally got down to the nitty-gritty.</p>\r\n<p>[!--empirenews.page--]</p>\r\n<p>462. nitwit &ndash; idiot. He messes up everything in our department and is such a nitwit.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>463. no bed of roses &ndash; uncomfortable, unhappy situation. Their marriage is no bed of roses. They seem to always be fighting.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>464. no dice &ndash; no, certainly not. I like living in this area. When my children wanted to move, I said &lsquo;no dice&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>465. no picnic &ndash; not pleasant. He works very hard at the factory. He says it is no picnic.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>466. nobody&rsquo;s fool &ndash; smart competent person. She&rsquo;s very smart. She&rsquo;s nobody&rsquo;s fool.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>467. not on your life &ndash; definitely not, no way. There is not a chance I am going to drive 4 hours to go to that party&hellip;not on your life.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>468. not so hot &ndash; not very good. She boasted about her pumpkin pie, but I thought it was not so hot.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>469. nothing to sneeze at &ndash; something not trivial, to be taken seriously. They offered him a lot of money to take this new position. He was going to give it a lot of thought because it was nothing to sneeze at.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>470. nuts about &ndash; in love with, enthusiastic about. I&rsquo;m nuts about our new neighbors.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>471. odds and ends &ndash; miscellaneous items. I have some odds and ends around my house that I would like to sell.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>472. off and on &ndash; occasionally. We are not very good friends anymore. I see him off and on.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>473. off base &ndash; inaccurate. If you think I paid one thousand dollars for this coat, you are way off base.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>474. off color - in bad taste, rude, dirty. He told an off-color joke at the party that embarrassed my wife.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>475. off one&rsquo;s rocker &ndash; crazy. He is off of his rocker if he thinks I&rsquo;m going to help him decorate for the party.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>476. off the hook &ndash; out of something, freed from an embarrassing situation. I don&rsquo;t want to have dinner with him. Let&rsquo;s tell him that we will be out of town so that we will get off the hook.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>477. off the record &ndash; privately, unofficially, not for public announcement. I need to tell you about one of my accounts, but it needs to be off the record.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>478. off the top of one&rsquo;s head &ndash; from memory, spontaneously. Off the top of my head, I think her last name begins with an &lsquo;M&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>479. old flame &ndash; former boyfriend or girlfriend. She bumped into an old flame at the shopping mall.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>480. on a shoestring &ndash; with very little money. We are trying to decorate our home on a shoestring.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>481. on easy street &ndash; having a pleasant, secure life. Ever since his mother won the lottery, they have been on easy street.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>482. on guard &ndash; careful, wary. It is a very important meeting and we must think before we speak. We must be on guard.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>483. on one&rsquo;s last leg &ndash; at the end of one&rsquo;s strength of usefulness. My car is over ten years old and it&rsquo;s on its last leg.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>484. on one&rsquo;s shoulders &ndash; one&rsquo;s responsibility. The president has a lot of problems on his shoulders.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>485. on pins and needles &ndash; nervous, excited. When I found out that the movie star was coming to the party, I was on pins and needles.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>486. on shaky ground &ndash; unstable. The buyers aren&rsquo;t sure if they really want to buy the car. I think the sale is on shaky ground.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>487. on the ball &ndash; paying attention and doing things well. She always gets her paperwork submitted on time. She is always on the ball.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>488. on the blink &ndash; not working. The ice is melting in our freezer. I think it is on the blink.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>489. on the edge of one&rsquo;s seat &ndash; in nervous suspense. I have wanted to see this movie ever since I read the book. Now that it is about to start, I am on the edge of my seat.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>490. on the fritz &ndash; not working correctly, out of order. The ice is melting in our freezer. I think it is on the fritz.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>491. on the go &ndash; busy running around. I won&rsquo;t be home all day. I have many errands to run and will be on the go.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>492. on the house &ndash; provided free by a bar or restaurant. Since I am good friends with the owner of the restaurant, dinner was on the house.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>493. on the level- honest. They are not telling you the whole story. They are not on the level.</p>\r\n<p>[!--empirenews.page--]</p>\r\n<p>494. on the q.t. &ndash; secretly. I was just told that I will be promoted to vicepresident but nobody knows about it yet. Please don&rsquo;t tell anyone and keep it on the q.t.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>495. on the rocks &ndash; breaking up, ruined. The couple is always fighting and I wasn&rsquo;t surprised to hear that their marriage is on the rocks.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>496. on the same wavelength &ndash; communicating, thinking similarly. They didn&rsquo;t understand each other. They were not on the same wavelength.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>497. on the spot &ndash; in a difficult or embarrassing situation. I was put on the spot and expected to make a toast at the anniversary party.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>498. on the wagon &ndash; abstaining from liquor. He used to drink a lot of beer and wine, but now he is on the wagon.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>499. on the warpath &ndash; very angry, looking for trouble. When Mary saw John with another woman, Mary went on the warpath.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>500. once in a blue moon &ndash; occasionally. He doesn&rsquo;t watch television often. Only once in a blue moon.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),
(41, 33, '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '<p>&nbsp;基于帝国cms的内容管理和投票系统。</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\\"/d/file/projects/2015-03-06/e9ce6eddfd4b32a8fa060fb0d239b495.jpg\\" alt=\\"y1.jpg\\" width=\\"1438\\" height=\\"1449\\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\\"/d/file/projects/2015-03-06/f79bbfd23460d54a1573f868d35b0d18.jpg\\" alt=\\"y2.jpg\\" width=\\"1438\\" height=\\"1224\\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\\"/d/file/projects/2015-03-06/6ece55bbfc6ea295ad4ac1cce7890c13.jpg\\" alt=\\"y3.jpg\\" width=\\"1438\\" height=\\"1431\\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\\"/d/file/projects/2015-03-06/619077c628582dbebea26db3d5266af1.jpg\\" alt=\\"y4.jpg\\" width=\\"958\\" height=\\"429\\" /></p>'),
(42, 10, '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '<p>实现对列表页和文章页的投票按钮点击进行投票，这里mervyn用&ldquo;顶&rdquo;的功能来修改实现。</p>\r\n<p>投票规则是：每个ip每天最多可投三票，提交需要输入验证码。</p>\r\n<p>一 、/e/下建立一个个人文件夹，此次我建立的文件夹名称是mervyn。把/e/public/下的digg文件夹复制进去。</p>\r\n<p>二、建立三个文件用于实现验证码。ckcode.php、code.php、showcode.php ;</p>\r\n<p>相关文件：mervyn.rar</p>\r\n<div style=\\"padding:6px\\"><fieldset>\r\n<table cellpadding=\\"0\\" cellspacing=\\"0\\" border=\\"0\\">\r\n    <tbody>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td><img src=\\"/e/data/images/downfile.jpg\\" alt=\\"文件类型: .rar\\" border=\\"0\\" style=\\"vertical-align:baseline\\" /></td>\r\n            <td><a href=\\"/d/file/web_dev/php/2015-03-06/f699b29d624f1b43b0e3fc76bdbbfdb3.rar\\" title=\\"mervyn.rar\\" target=\\"_blank\\">f699b29d624f1b43b0e3fc76bdbbfdb3.rar</a>&nbsp;(3.35 KB)</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</fieldset></div>\r\n<div>三、开始前台调用</div>\r\n<div>文章列表：</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<pre><p>&lt;ul&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">	</span>[e:loop={9,4,0,1,\\''\\'',\\''diggtop DESC\\''}]</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">	</span>&lt;li&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">		</span>&lt;div class=&quot;indexMainListPic&quot;&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">			</span>&lt;a href=&quot;&lt;?=$bqsr[\\''titleurl\\'']?&gt;&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">				</span>&lt;img src=&quot;&lt;?=$bqr[\\''titlepic\\'']?&gt;&quot; /&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">			</span>&lt;/a&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">		</span>&lt;/div&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">		</span>&lt;h3&gt;&lt;?=$bqr[\\''title\\'']?&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">		</span>&lt;div class=&quot;indexMainListTool&quot;&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">			</span>&lt;p&gt;票数：&lt;span&gt;&lt;?=$bqr[\\''diggtop\\''];?&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">			</span>&lt;a href=&quot;javascript:void(0)&quot; name=&quot;tou&quot; aid=&quot;&lt;?=$bqr[\\''id\\'']?&gt;&quot; classid=&quot;&lt;?=$bqr[\\''classid\\'']?&gt;&quot;&gt;投一票&lt;/a&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">		</span>&lt;/div&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">	</span>&lt;/li&gt;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\\"Apple-tab-span\\" style=\\"white-space: pre;\\">	</span>[/e:loop]</p>\r\n<p>&lt;/ul&gt;</p>\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>jquery代码：</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<pre class=\\"brush:js;toolbar:false\\">\r\n$(function(){\r\n	$(&quot;a[name=\\''tou\\'']&quot;).each(function(){\r\n		$(this).click(function(){\r\n			var diggs=$(this).parent(&quot;.indexMainListTool&quot;).find(&quot;span&quot;);\r\n			var curdiggs=diggs.text();//当前票数\r\n			var aid=$(this).attr(&quot;aid&quot;);//文章id\r\n			var classid=$(this).attr(&quot;classid&quot;);//栏目id\r\n			var t=$(window).scrollTop();\r\n			var h=$(&quot;#floater&quot;).height();\r\n			var newt=t-h/2;\r\n			$(&quot;#cover&quot;).show();//遮罩层\r\n			$(&quot;#floater&quot;).css(&quot;margin-top&quot;,newt+&quot;px&quot;).show().load(&quot;[!--news.url--]e/mervyn/showcode.php&quot;,&quot;&quot;,function(){//验证码窗口\r\n				$(&quot;#floater .sub&quot;).click(function(){\r\n					var code=$(&quot;input[name=\\''code\\'']&quot;).val();\r\n					var d={&quot;code&quot;:code};		\r\n					$.ajax({\r\n						type:&quot;post&quot;,\r\n						url:&quot;[!--news.url--]e/mervyn/ckcode.php&quot;,\r\n						data:d,\r\n						dataType:&quot;json&quot;,\r\n						success:function(data){\r\n							var msg=data.msg;//yes or no\r\n							if(msg==&quot;no&quot;){\r\n								alert(&quot;验证码错误&quot;);\r\n								return false;\r\n							}else if(msg==&quot;yes&quot;){//验证码正确 执行投票\r\n								var dd={&quot;aid&quot;:aid,&quot;classid&quot;:classid};	\r\n								//alert(aid);  2\r\n								//alert(classid); 6\r\n								$.ajax({\r\n									type:&quot;post&quot;,\r\n									url:&quot;[!--news.url--]e/mervyn/digg/index.php&quot;,\r\n									data:dd,\r\n									dataType:&quot;json&quot;,\r\n									success:function(data){\r\n										// alert(data);\r\n										if(data.valid!=&quot;yes&quot;){\r\n											alert(data.msg);//投票失败\r\n											$(&quot;#floater&quot;).empty().hide();\r\n											$(&quot;#cover&quot;).hide();\r\n										}else{\r\n											alert(&quot;感谢您的支持&quot;);\r\n											//更新投票数\r\n											var newdiggs=parseInt(curdiggs)+1;\r\n											diggs.text(newdiggs);\r\n											$(&quot;#floater&quot;).empty().hide();\r\n											$(&quot;#cover&quot;).hide();\r\n										}\r\n									}\r\n								})\r\n							}\r\n						},\r\n						error:function(){\r\n							\r\n						}\r\n					})\r\n				})\r\n			});\r\n		})\r\n	})\r\n})</pre>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!--2800;$i++)<-->\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!--$len;$i++){<-->\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!--?php<-->\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!--?php<-->\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
